In TypeScript, you can use the "type guard" pattern to tell the type system that a value may have multiple types in theory, but in practice it will only have a single type. A type guard is a way of checking a value at runtime to determine its type, and then using that information to restrict the type of that value in subsequent code.

For example, let's say you have a function that takes an input parameter of type "number | string", which means it can accept either a number or a string. But in reality, you know that the input will always be a number. You can use a type guard to check the input at runtime and then restrict its type to number.

Here's an example:
```typescript
function add(input: number | string): number {
  if (typeof input === 'number') {
    // Type of 'input' is now restricted to 'number'
    return input + 1;
  } else {
    throw new Error('Invalid input');
  }
}
```
In this example, we use the typeof operator to check whether the input parameter is a number or a string. If it's a number, we return the result of adding 1 to it. But if it's a string, we throw an error. This way, we've used a type guard to restrict the type of the input parameter to number in our function body.

Another common pattern for using type guards is with the "in" operator. For example, if you have an object with properties of different types, you can use the "in" operator to check whether a particular property exists and then use that information to restrict the type of that property.
```typescript
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age?: number;
}

function greet(person: Person) {
  if ('age' in person) {
    // Type of 'person.age' is now restricted to 'number'
    console.log(`Hello ${person.name}, you are ${person.age} years old`);
  } else {
    console.log(`Hello ${person.name}`);
  }
}
```
In this example, we use the "in" operator to check whether the person object has an age property. If it does, we know that the age property must be a number, so we restrict its type in our function body.

It's important to note that while type guards can be useful for enforcing types at runtime, they do not provide complete protection against bugs or invalid inputs. It's still possible for bugs or invalid inputs to slip through and cause errors or unexpected behavior. Therefore, it's always important to exercise caution when working with type guards and to ensure that your code is well-tested and documented.

Here's a sample C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  string word; // the word to search for
  int count = 0; // variable to store the count

  // prompt user to enter the word to search for
  cout << "Enter the word to search for: ";
  getline(cin, word);

  // open the input file
  ifstream infile("input.txt");

  // read each line of the file and count the occurrences of the word
  string line;
  while (getline(infile, line)) {
    size_t pos = line.find(word);
    while (pos != string::npos) {
      count++;
      pos = line.find(word, pos + 1);
    }
  }

  // print the count
  cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" appears " << count << " times in the file." << endl;

  return 0;
}

In this program, we use an ifstream object to read from an input file called "input.txt". We use getline to read each line of the file and find the occurrences of the given word. We increment the count variable for each occurrence found. Finally, we print the count to the console.

